To further explore the optical properties of the prepared SCDs, UV–vis absorption and PL spectroscopic characterizations were carried out (Fig. 2
                        ). It is obvious from the UV–vis spectrogram that the SCDs suspension shows two absorption peaks at 263 and 370 nm (Fig. 2A, line a), which is similar to the reported literatures [14,26,27]. The absorption bond at ∼263 nm without PL signal is attributed to the σ → π and/or π → π* electronic transitions of aromatic sp2
                         domains [21,24], indicating that the PL of SCDs are not generated by the aromatic conjugate skeleton. The other transition, centered at ∼370 nm, is attributed to the trapping of excited state energy of the C = N/C = O/C-S groups originated from the SCDs skeleton [28,29]. Upon excitation with a 370 nm beam (Fig. 2A, line c), a strong PL emission peak appears at 450 nm with a Stokes shift of 80 nm (Fig. 2A, line b). Like the most reported carbon-based probes [11,30,31], the emission wavelength of SCDs does not shift as the excitation wavelength changes from 330 to 410 nm, which is independent of the excitation wavelength, indicating the influence of particle sizes or distribution of different surface states (Fig. 2B). Therefore, the PL of SCDs depends on the surface states rather than the different sizes.
